<section xml:id="sec_paren">
  <title>Parentheses</title>
  <p>
    One of the greatest challenges to students is using parentheses correctly to help a calculator interpret a formula correctly.
    For example, consider the expression
    <me>
      \frac{1+7}{2}
    </me>.
  </p>
  <p>
    We know from elementary school that you compute the whole numerator of the fraction before dividing by the denominator,
    so this expression equals <m>4</m>.
    If you type it into the calculator without parentheses,
    however, we get \calcscreen{1+7/2
  </p>
  <p>
    \ca 4.5} That's because the calculator,
    following the order of operations we learned as children,
    first does the division and then the addition:
    <m>\texttt{7/2} = 3.5</m>, so <m>\texttt{1+7/2}=4.5</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    We human beings can tell,
    by looking at <m>\frac{1+7}{2}</m>,
    that the <m>1+7</m> has to be done first,
    but the calculator doesn't know that unless we tell it.
    So we should really type \calcscreen{(1+7)/2
  </p>
  <p>
    \ca 4} One way to make this process easier,
    especially in long complicated formulas,
    is to draw in the extra parentheses on your paper before you begin typing into the calculator.
    <me>
      \mbox{Given~} \frac{1+7}{2},\mbox{~draw in~} \frac{\textcolor{red}{(}1+7\textcolor{red}{)}}{2}\mbox{~and then type~} \texttt{(1+7)/2}
    </me>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Here are some locations that typically need extra parentheses:
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          The numerator of a fraction:
          <m>\dfrac{1+7}{2}</m> becomes <m>\dfrac{\textcolor{red}{(}1+7\textcolor{red}{)}}{2}</m>.
          <tabular>
            <row>
              <cell><em>Incorrect:</em></cell>
              <cell><em>Correct:</em>
                <sidebyside>
                  1+7/2 \ca 4.5
                </sidebyside></cell>
              <cell><sidebyside>
                  (1+7)/2 \ca 4
                </sidebyside></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          The denominator of a fraction:
          <m>\dfrac{\quad8}{\frac{6}{3}}</m> becomes <m>\dfrac{\quad8}{\textcolor{red}{(}\frac{6}{3}\textcolor{red}{)}}</m>.
          <tabular>
            <row>
              <cell><em>Incorrect:</em></cell>
              <cell><em>Correct:</em>
                <sidebyside>
                  8/6/3 \ca 0.444444
                </sidebyside></cell>
              <cell><sidebyside>
                  8/(6/3) \ca 4
                </sidebyside></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Exponents:<fn>
          Some more recent Texas Instrument calculators help you out by making exponents actually look like exponents.
          On such a calculator,
          if you press the keys <kbd>5</kbd> <kbd>\caret</kbd> <kbd>6</kbd> <kbd>-</kbd> <kbd>4</kbd> , it will display as \calcscreen{<m>5^{6-4}</m> \ca 25} On this kind of calculator,
          if you need to type more <em>after</em> the exponent,
          press the right arrow key \rightkey<nbsp/>to get
          <q>back down</q>
          to the main line.
          For example, to evaluate <m>5^{6-4}+7</m> on such a calculator,
          you would press the buttons <kbd>5</kbd> <kbd>\caret</kbd> <kbd>6</kbd> <kbd>-</kbd> <kbd>4</kbd> \rightkey <kbd>+</kbd> <kbd>7</kbd> to get \calcscreen{<m>5^{6-4}+7</m> \ca 32}
          </fn> <m>5^{6-4}</m> becomes <m>5^{\textcolor{red}{(}6-4\textcolor{red}{)}}</m>.
          <tabular>
            <row>
              <cell><em>Incorrect:</em></cell>
              <cell><em>Correct:</em>
                <sidebyside>
                  5\caret6-4 \ca 15621
                </sidebyside></cell>
              <cell><sidebyside>
                  5\caret(6-4) \ca 25
                </sidebyside></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
  <p>
    Of course, one complicated expression may need all of these!
    <m>500\dfrac{\left(1+\frac{.07}{52}\right)^{8\cdot52}-1}{\frac{.07}{52}}</m> becomes <m>500\dfrac{\textcolor{red}{\Big(}\left(1+\frac{.07}{52}\right)^{\textcolor{red}{(}8\cdot52\textcolor{red}{)}}-1\textcolor{red}{\Big)}}{\textcolor{red}{(}\frac{.07}{52}\textcolor{red}{)}}</m>.
  </p>
  <tabular>
    <row>
      <cell><em>Incorrect:</em></cell>
      <cell><em>Correct:</em>
        <sidebyside>
          500*(1+.07/52)\caret8*52-1/
          .07/52
          \ca 26281.04806
        </sidebyside></cell>
      <cell><sidebyside>
          500*((1+.07/52)\caret(8*52)
          -1)/(.07/52)
          \ca 278576.3860
        </sidebyside></cell>
    </row>
  </tabular>
</section>